              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> Our word “apocrypha” comes from the Greek plural <em>apocrypha</em> (sing. <em>apocryphon</em>), which means “hidden.” The word often has a pejorative meaning of “spurious” and sometimes “esoteric.” Biblical Apocrypha range from works that fit this pejorative connotation and others that do not. (🡨 these first three lines need to be moved to first mention of “apocryphal” on Pg 38 or so) The Book of Enoch, while apocryphal, is generally well regarded. It is actually made up of two separate books, the Ethiopian Book of Enoch (sometimes referred to as 1 Enoch) and the Slavonic Book of Enoch (2 Enoch). The Book of Enoch is not known to exist in any manuscript written in its original language but only in Ethiopic and Slavonic. It is of note that both 1 Enoch and 2 Enoch present a universalistic attitude toward Prophetic religion very different from the nationalistic narrowness of Pharisaic Judaism. </p>",
