              "markerKey": "book-four-god-s-messenger-noah-nuh-the-cataclysmic-universal-flood:syntopicon:16",
              "origin": "syntopicon",
              "content": "<p> As a Lawgiver, Noah enjoined his progeny to live by the seven Noachian laws, which the Qur’ān alludes to: “He has prescribed for you [as Law] what He enjoined upon Noah and what We have revealed unto you and what We enjoined upon Abraham, Moses, and Jesus, that you uphold religion and not become divided in it…” (Counsel, 42:13; cf. 4:163-164). The Seven Laws of Noah are the prohibition 1) of worshipping idols, 2) cursing in God’s name, 3) murder, 4) adultery and sexual immorality, 5) theft, 6), eating flesh torn from a living animal, as well as 7) the obligation to establish courts of justice. These Laws are said to be universal and to pertain to all human beings. After Christ’s Ascension in early years of his mission, the Jerusalem Church required converts to Jesus’s message who were not of the Children of Israel to abide by the Noachian Laws, but they were not required to observe Mosaic Law, which remained obligatory for Judaic Christians. </p>",
